'''''The Quarrel of Oberon and Titania''''' is an oil on canvas painting by the Scottish artist Sir [[Joseph Noel Paton]]. Painted in 1849, it depicts the scene from [[William Shakespeare]]'s comedy play ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]'', when the fairy queen [[Titania]] and fairy king [[Oberon]] quarrel; Oberon was considered the King of the fairies in medieval and Renaissance literature.  When exhibited in Edinburgh during 1850, it was declared as the "painting of the season".{{r|National}} It was acquired by the [[National Galleries of Scotland]] in 1897, having initially been bought by the Royal Association for Promoting the Fine Arts in Scotland during 1850. An earlier version of this painting was Paton's diploma picture, which was submitted to the [[Royal Scottish Academy]] in 1846; they paid £700 for it.

==Description==
The overall dimensions of the oil on canvas painting are {{convert|99|by|152|cm}}.{{r|BBC}} Based on [[William Shakespeare]]'s comedy play ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]'', it depicts a scene in which the fairy queen [[Titania]] and fairy king [[Oberon]] quarrel with each other. Oberon was considered the King of the fairies in medieval and Renaissance literature. The scene depicts Act II, scene i,{{r|Emory}} put into an enchanting imaginary landscape when Oberon is arguing with Titania,{{sfnp|Jacobson|2004|p=30|ps=}} just as nightfall descends.{{sfnp|Wood|2008|p=92|ps=}} The setting is the couple's woodland home outside Athens and they are surrounded by a group of fairies.{{sfnp|Jacobson|2004|p=30|ps=}} According to [[Lewis Carroll]], the author of ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'', 165 fairies are in the painting.{{r|National}} The subject of the couple's argument is the [[changeling]] boy,{{sfnp|Wood|2008|p=89|ps=}} who is hiding behind Titania.{{sfnp|Wood|2008|p=90|ps=}} A lily pond is at the front of the painting and the woodland setting is made up from leaves, flowers and aged twisted trees.{{sfnp|Wood|2008|p=90|ps=}} Titania's head is encircled by a group of fairies forming a bright crown of light.{{sfnp|Wood|2008|p=90|ps=}} A statue of [[Pan (god)|Pan]] with a set of pipes is placed to the right of the picture with several couples in a state of undress positioned beneath it.{{sfnp|Wood|2008|p=90|ps=}} [[Goblin]]s mingle with [[elf|elves]] and [[imp]]s that all cavort among the nude fairies;{{sfnp|Wood|2008|p=90|ps=}} some other little, ugly figures are scattered throughout together with moths, beetles, spiders and snails.{{sfnp|Wood|2008|p=91|ps=}}

Paton's earlier work in 1847, ''The Reconciliation of Oberon and Titania'', was considered by Paton to be "related yet self-contained".{{r|Victorian}}

==Exhibitions and provenance==
First exhibited at the [[Royal Scottish Academy]] in 1850,{{r|Sothebys}} where it was declared to be the "painting of the season",{{r|National}} the picture was purchased by the Royal Association for Promoting the Fine Arts in Scotland during that year.{{r|National}} The ''Quarrel'' was later displayed at the Paris Exhibition in 1855,{{r|Western}} being listed as "Representative of British Art".{{r|Paisley}} It passed to the ownership of the [[National Galleries of Scotland]] in 1897.{{r|National}} An earlier study of this painting was completed in 1846 and featured as Paton's diploma picture{{r|Reconciliation}} at the Royal Scottish Academy that year.{{r|Victorian}} The Academy purchased the earlier work for £700.{{sfnp|Oxford University Press|2012|p=193|ps=}}

According to Richard Schindler, Associate Professor of Art at [[Allegheny College]],{{r|Allegheny}} the piece bears influences from the works of [[Henry Fuseli]], an opinion shared by Carole Silver, a professor with a particular interest in the [[Victorian era|19th-century]] fascination with fairies.{{sfnp|Silver|2000|p=215|ps=}}{{sfnp|Haase|2007|p=1158|ps=}} Christopher Wood, an expert in Victorian art,{{r|Telegraph}} described Paton's work as being "some of the most remarkable fairy pictures".{{sfnp|Wood|2008|p=86|ps=}}

